description.plain:
Gifted with one of the finest voices of the early 21st century and exceptional talent, the famed Alicia Keys is a recognized, award-winning R&B singer, songwriter, and record producer. She was born on January 25, 1981 in New York.

Her debut album Songs in A Minor launched her career as she became the best-selling new artist of 2001. Her follow-up album The Diary of Alicia Keys (2003) and her album for the MTV Unplugged series in 2005 further cemented her at the top of the pop and R&B game. Her biggest hits are powerful ballads like “Fallin',” “If I Ain’t Got You,” and “No One.”

On January 15, 2019 Pop/R&B legend and 15-time GRAMMY winner Alicia Keys was announced as the host of the 61st Annual GRAMMY Awards. This will be the first time Keys has been the master of ceremonies for Music’s Biggest Night.

Alicia Keys, whose birth name is Alicia Augello-Cook, has been married to rapper and producer Swizz Beats since 2010 from whom she has two children: Egypt Daoud and Genesis Ali.

songs.full_title: No One by Alicia Keys
songs.title: No One

description.plain:
“No One” details the idea that no matter what happens in life, the person you love will always be there for you.

In an interview with Billboard, Keys said:

This is one song that just wrote itself. A lot of the songs didn’t happen like that. It was one of the last songs I wrote. I needed to say this. It’s full force, classical yet vintage, desperate yet triumphant. I want people to feel my soul.

Keys performed “No One” with John Mayer at the 2008 Grammy Awards, where it was awarded Best R&B Song and Best Female R&B Vocal Performance.

Aretha Franklin also covered this for her 2014 album, Aretha Franklin Sings the Great Diva Classics.

songs.full_title: Fallin' by Alicia Keys
songs.title: Fallin’

description.plain:
“Fallin” is the successful lead single from Alicia Keys' debut studio album Songs in A Minor. The single gained worldwide success, earning Key’s three Grammy Awards out of 4 nominated, number 1 record on the US Billboard Hot 100 and being praised as the 29th most successful song of the early 2000s.

When asked about the background behind the song, Keys told Billboard, “I wanted to write a song for someone who was 10 or 12 years old – like a young Michael Jackson. Even though he was young, he was singing some deep stuff back then. [The song] is about the ins and outs of a relationship. Sometimes, you’re completely head-over-heels in love with someone, and sometimes you can’t stand that person. You fall in and out, sometimes it goes back and forth, and that’s just what relationships are about.” The song samples the early James Brown hit, “It’s a Man’s Man’s Man’s World.”

songs.full_title: Un-Thinkable (I'm Ready) by Alicia Keys
songs.title: Un-Thinkable (I’m Ready)

description.plain:
Another love-themed song on Alicia’s 4th studio album, The Element of Freedom.
While the theme of the song seems quite simple, it’s about a starting relationship where both persons think the relationship is something un-thinkable. The video from the song seemed to show the song’s true colors.

The music video shows the hardship an interracial couple- the brown Alicia playing the girl and the white Chad Michael Murray as the boy- has to go through since the brother of the girl doesn’t approve of her choice in men.

The music video shows that this song is more than a simple love song and can be interpreted as a more societal statement underlining that people should be free to chase their feelings regardless of color and the subjective norm: chase what seems un-thinkable.

songs.full_title: Underdog by Alicia Keys
songs.title: Underdog

description.plain:
“Underdog” is an uptempo R&B song about people working for a better life, released as the third single off of Alicia Keys‘ upcoming seventh studio album, A.L.I.C.I.A..

Alicia announced the song on January 8, 2020, on social media, and released the song the day after, with a music video directed by Wendy Morgan. According to Complex, “the visual focuses on everyday people who spend their days hustling in pursuit of a better life.”

The track was co-written by Keys herself, English singer-songwriter Ed Sheeran, Irish singer-songwriter Foy Vance, and songwriters Amy Wadge, Jonny Coffer, and Johnny McDaid, while co-produced by Keys and McDaid.

songs.full_title: In Common by Alicia Keys
songs.title: In Common

description.plain:
“In Common” is Alicia Key’s first single since 2012’s “Girl On Fire” and places Key’s soft but soulful vocals over smooth tropical beats. The song centers around the idea that “opposites attract”, but in this case Keys and her lover ultimately have too many common traits to be together.

Keys debuted “In Common” as well as “Hallelujah” on the May 7th episode of Saturday Night Live  after she teased that new songs were on the way in a Snapchat video.

songs.full_title: Blended Family (What You Do For Love) by Alicia Keys (Ft. A$AP Rocky & Tish Hyman)
songs.title: Blended Family (What You Do For Love)
songs.title_with_featured: Blended Family (What You Do For Love) (Ft. A$AP Rocky & Tish Hyman)

description.plain:
“Blended Family” continues the musical evolution undertaken on previous single “In Common,” whilst delivering the listener open-heart expressions by both Keys and Rocky. The subject matter is a celebration of families with complicated stories.

Alicia and Rocky share memories and anecdotes about their families. She references her marriage to Swizz Beatz, and her love for the children he brought into their relationship from his previous marriage to singer Mashonda Tifrere,. Rocky delivers a moving verse on his childhood memories and the support he received from various family members.

“Blended Family (What You Do For Love),” features fellow New York native A$AP Rocky, and is the second single from Alicia Keys' sixth studio album HERE. The track premiered on the 6th of October on Tidal, iTunes and other music outlets.

songs.full_title: Fire We Make by Alicia Keys (Ft. Maxwell)
songs.title: Fire We Make

description.plain:
“Fire We Make” is track number seven off Alicia Keys' fifth studio album Girl On Fire. It topped Billboard’s Adult R&B chart, making it Keys' tenth #1 on the chart.

This sensual duet with Maxwell talks about how Alicia and her partner get “hotter” every time they come into contact, hence the name “Fire We Make.”

https://youtu.be/gN-az8fkaKc

Maxwell had nothing but positive things to say when he talked about how it was working with Alicia.

She’s just sweet, genuine, people. I mean, she’s Alicia Keys. I’ve been a fan for a minute. She’s very professional. I went in and I was like, ‘What do you want me to do?’ and she was like, ‘This is the song. You just do what you do, and we’ll see what happens.’ It was one of the best studio experiences I’ve ever had.

songs.full_title: Brand New Me by Alicia Keys
songs.title: Brand New Me

description.plain:
“Brand New Me” is the second track on Alicia Keys' 2012 album, Girl on Fire. Alicia calls it the “anchor” of the record and speaking on Capital FM Radio she explained:

“Brand New Me” is one of my favorites, it’s going to be my second single and to me it’s like my autobiography. It says everything about everywhere that I’ve come and who I am now. It’s about being completely happy with finding yourself.

The song is a slow burning declaration of self-esteem which finds Keys confronting an old lover and offering him the chance to get to know the new version of herself.

The title of the song implies that the track provides a sense of self-release… and so does the music video:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wOSv1TIa58M

In an interview with Complex magazine, she expressed her love for the song by saying:

Don’t be mad that I’m different […] Don’t be mad that I’m changed. Don’t be mad that I’m grown. You can’t affect me the way you once did. You can’t be mad. Like, how could you be mad? […] I love that song so much. It’s so freaking real.

songs.full_title: Superwoman by Alicia Keys
songs.title: Superwoman

description.plain:
Alicia Keys' hit single off her album “As I Am” reached the 12th spot on the US Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs and was the 2008 opening song to WNBA games.

The song/video captures the every day woman from all parts of the world and financial structures. Superwoman is any woman who can provide for herself and the ones she loves. The music video shows women in different situations, how they provide and the struggles they go through.

In an interview with New York Times Alicia Keys said:

This song is a reminder to myself that even when I’m out, and I’m just a mess, and I’m not perfect, and everything’s not great, and I’m struggling to figure out what is what – I’m still a superwoman.

This song also won the Grammy Award for Best Female R&B Vocal Performance in 2009.

songs.full_title: Holy War by Alicia Keys
songs.title: Holy War

description.plain:
“Holy War” is the sixteenth track from Alicia Keys' sixth studio album HERE.

During a speech at the 2016 MTV Video Music Awards, Alicia teased the song as a poem while she was presenting the award for “Best Male Video.”
https://youtu.be/Jv5_VtOPpxg

In an interview with Rolling Stone, she talked about the meaning behind this song.

We get so afraid to talk to our kids about sex, or we wanna hide all of our body parts and don’t let anybody see the beauty of love and lovemaking, yet we let kids play Call of Duty all day and all night, and that’s, like, no problem? It’s very confusing and twisted.

songs.full_title: 3 Hour Drive by Alicia Keys (Ft. Sampha)
songs.title: 3 Hour Drive

description.plain: On the Netflix show, Song Exploder, Alicia Keys, Sampha, and Jimmy Napes go into detail on how the song developed. Alicia Keys came to London to work on music with Jimmy Naples following the birth of her second child. Sampha joined them, feeling keenly the recent loss of his mother. Working together in a single session, they started by developing ideas for melodies and beats. They played with vocal tones, forming them into lyrical phrases, including that of the song’s title and the central phrase of the chorus, “you give me life.” Having developed a verse, they then realized the possibilities of mirroring the same words with different delivery by the two singers. In the end, the song became a meditation on the circular nature of life, the joy and grief of arrivals and departures that make up the typical arc of our existence.

songs.full_title: Good Job by Alicia Keys
songs.title: Good Job

description.plain:
“Good Job,” the fourth single off Alicia Keys' album ALICIA, is an anthem of thanks to everyday people – that though their jobs may feel small, their hard work and perseverance still matters.

The song has taken on increased meaning during the COVID-19 crisis – which delayed the release of Keys' record – as parents have taken on the extra responsibility of homeschooling their children and governments around the world have had to distinguish between “essential” and “non-essential” workers.

Keys premiered a music video for this song on CNN during an April 23 digital town hall. A press release announcing the collaboration explains the lyrics' changing significance for the veteran songwriter:


The song was originally written to recognize and celebrate unsung heroes in Keys’ life, like her mom who she watched struggle as a single woman in New York’s Hell’s Kitchen, and many others who she saw were often overlooked. In the wake of the current global pandemic, she realized her message coincidentally fit the moment.

“Whether you’re on the frontlines at the hospitals, balancing work, family and homeschool teaching, delivering mail, packages, or food, or facing other personal difficulties because of COVID-19, I feel you. You are seen, loved and deeply appreciated,” said Keys.

“The Gospel” was premiered live at the Apple Music Festival and in order to accompany the release of the album, Alicia released her short film The Gospel, which is available exclusively on Tidal;
The 23 minute film addresses the issue of police brutality in NYC, directed by A.V. Rockwell, and made its debut at the Tribeca Film Festival in April 2016.

description.plain:
“She Don’t Really Care” is another hometown anthem from New York native Alicia Keys. Keys premiered it during her set at the Apple Music Festival in London in September 2016:

It’s really the most purposeful and most intentional that I’ve ever written music before, ever, and it’s all about New York City in so many ways, which is why I’m bringing you into my world a little bit.

songs.full_title: Time Machine by Alicia Keys
songs.title: Time Machine

description.plain:
“Time Machine” is the lead single from Alicia Keys‘ upcoming seventh studio album, A.L.I.C.I.A.. According to Rolling Stone, “the song’s lyrics focus on letting go of hang-ups and finding freedom”.

On the day of the song’s release, November 21st, 2019, Alicia said in a Q&A Twitter session that the track was inspired by Biggie, Michael Jackson and the funkadelic genre.

songs.full_title: Doesn't Mean Anything by Alicia Keys
songs.title: Doesn’t Mean Anything

description.plain:
“Doesn’t Mean Anything” was the lead single for Alicia Keys' fourth album, The Element of Freedom. It was unveiled online on September 15, 2009 before hitting shelves and online stores on September 22. Even though the musical direction of the album differed from Keys' previous releases, the song was compared to her preceding hits “No One” and “If I Ain’t Got You.” The song charted in 21 different countries or regions, Going #3 in Japan and #2 on the Billboard’s Adult R&B chart.

A music video directed by P.R. Brown was released on October 19, 2009 and charted on BET’s Notarized Year-end countdown show. In the video, Keys opens up on an apartment balcony, saying:

This beautiful city seems empty. All the people in the world and you can still feel lonely. What’s the point of having it all without the person you love. Sometimes you just need to start again in order to fly.

songs.full_title: Girl Can’t Be Herself by Alicia Keys
songs.title: Girl Can’t Be Herself

description.plain:
“Girl Can’t Be Herself” is an anthem for Alicia’s makeup-free movement, and alludes to the expectations of women in the media and in society.

Alicia launched her #NoMakeup campaign in 2016, which she first brought to everyone’s attention after she penned an open letter in Lena Dunham’s Lenny Letter in May 2016. She explained that her stand against using makeup was supposed to inspire people to love each other for what’s on the inside rather than on the outside:

It would be so amazing to just embrace each other how we are. I think the most important thing is you do what feels good for you.

songs.full_title: How Come You Don't Call Me by Alicia Keys
songs.title: How Come You Don’t Call Me
songs.title_with_featured: How Come You Don't Call Me

description.plain:
“How Come You Don’t Call Me” is the 3rd track on Alicia Keys' inaugural album, Songs in A Minor. It became its 3rd single on June 4, 2002, reaching #3 in Belgium and #4 in Hungary as well in the Top 50 in 8 other regions.

This is a cover of “How Come U Don’t Call Me Anymore?” written, sung, and released by Prince in 1982. Critically, it was viewed as sufficient in comparison to the original, but not as well done as Stephanie Mills 1983 version.
Alicia’s cover was inspired by a previous long-term relationship, according to Vibe and she was quoted in Billboard as saying:

I had never heard [the original] before. They gave me a copy of the song on tape. I played it every day for three weeks. It is so raw and so truthful – I was just feeling it. It really came out well.

Regardless, it’s still notable that she rejuvenated popularity in the song. She performed it on occasion, including with Prince at the LA Forum in 2011:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B1vmwdllCPg

description.plain:
This song was originally intended to be on her second studio album, The Diary Of Alicia Keys, but she felt like it would fit better here.

The song was always one of my favorites, but I did not think it would fit well into my second album.

The track is built around a sample of Eddie Kendrick’s 1977 song “Intimate Friends”.

 The lyrics mention the names of several well-known couples, some of whom include Tina Turner, Bill and Camille Cosby, Oprah Winfrey and Stedman Graham, Florida and James Evans, Will and Jada Pinkett Smith, Kimora Lee and Russel Simmons, and Joe and Katherine Jackson, as well as The Jackson 5.

songs.full_title: Raise a Man by Alicia Keys
songs.title: Raise a Man

description.plain:
In the song, Alicia Keys tries to explain the sentiment behind what it’s like to exist in a marriage that is overflowing with love and how she wants to teach her young son how to love another woman the way her husband loves her.

Alicia uses descriptive imagery and metaphorical speech to describe the depth of
 how she perceives and experiences love.

To Alicia, Love is not just an emotion you experience but in fact, it’s a lifestyle that she believes everybody should live especially in today’s world.

In Western Societies today, the definition of character traits such as independence and strength is glorified while portraying their opposites, dependency, and vulnerability, as something to be avoided and belittled.

While being admirable characteristics, the song is meant to explore the entire spectrum of these traits to emphasize qualities such as vulnerability and dependency not as something negative but instead as a way of truly experiencing the world deeply and intimately without lacking in any virtue of character.

Alicia finally asks the listener that if they understood the depth of the message to show her their hands, thereby indicating that not only did they understand her message, but actually live it as well and whether perhaps they could show her just exactly how she could teach these lessons to her son.

songs.full_title: Tell You Something (Nana's Reprise) by Alicia Keys
songs.title: Tell You Something (Nana’s Reprise)

description.plain:
“Tell You Something” is the thirteenth track from American singer and Songwriter Alicia Keys for her third studio album, As I Am. Written and Produced by Keys, Kerry Brothers, Jr., Paul L. Green, Novel Stevenson, Ron Haney and Steve Mostyn. It was released as the single on November 2007, it peaked at No. 1 and No. 4 consecutive weeks from the R&B singles chart.

Alicia explained the song’s background to the Daily Mail on December 14, 2007.

Witnessing a loved one dying was very hard. She was one of the most influential women in my life and seeing her in pain wasn’t nice – there was nothing I could do. I tried to keep a positive outlook, but what will be will be. The song came from the feeling of knowing that I needed to say all these things to her while she was still there. There’s no point bringing flowers to somebody’s funeral. It’s more important to bring the flowers while your loved ones are still alive.

songs.title: Speechless

description.plain:
Alicia Keys wrote this freestyle song with her husband Swizz Beats after her son Egypt was born. The song was released as a promo gift for Keys’s fans on Beatz’s Monster Monday program on December 27, 2010.



She explained the independence of the song on Twitter, stating that it wasn’t an album or a single.

‘Speechless’ was just a little freestyle treat for the holidays. It’s not a new album, not a single, it’s something special for you!

“Devil in a New Dress” by Kanye West feat. Rick Ross is also sampled in the song.

songs.title: Wait Til You See My Smile
songs.title_with_featured: Wait Til You See My Smile

description.plain: “Wait Til You See My Smile” is a song performed by American recording artist Alicia Keys. It was released as the sixth single (fourth in the UK) from her fourth studio album, The Element of Freedom (2009). The soul-pop ballad was released on December 13, 2010. The Keys and “Wait Till You See My Smile” featured on the new Samsung DualView Commercial. The song was featured on the 13th episode of the sixth season of Grey’s Anatomy.

songs.full_title: 28 Thousand Days by Alicia Keys
songs.title: 28 Thousand Days

description.plain:
“28 Thousand Days” is a single by Alicia Keys. This number is equal to 76 years, which is also the average human life expectancy. The song’s lyrics talk about living life to the fullest, never wasting time, and not missing one good moment.

According to The Boombox, Keys explained the meaning behind the song in a video she posted on Twitter.

Yo, I read this ill article that said the average life is 76 years which equals 28,000 days. That made me think that I gotta live every moment to the fullest. What you gonna do to make the most out of today? We gonna do a song about that.

She also tweeted:

This is just the beginning believe me! We have so much to talk about! Live everyday like its your last!! #28000days

Keys has expressed her desire for living life to the fullest and treating every moment like it’s the last, in several of her other songs too, such as “Like You’ll Never See Me Again”, “Tell You Something(Nana’s Reprise)”, “How It Feels To Fly', and “New Day'.

description.plain:
“When You Really Love Someone” is track number eleven off of Alicia Keys' second studio album The Diary Of Alicia Keys.

Throughout the song, she goes back and forth, talking about all the qualities a real man should have, and all the qualities a loving woman should have.

Love is repeatedly used as a verb to show that actions speak louder than words.

songs.full_title: Not Even the King by Alicia Keys
songs.title: Not Even the King

description.plain:
“Not Even the King” is track number nine off Alicia Keys’s fifth studio album Girl On Fire. This piano ballad serves as the sixth overall single from the album.

The song tells of a transcendent love that is so valuable a king could not even afford it, hence the title.

Keys wrote the song with Emeli Sandé, which was not the first time they had collaborated together. (Checkout “Hope”, “101”, and “Brand New Me”). They both had only positive things to say about each other.

Sandé explained:

 Writing with Alicia Keys was really great. I was nervous, but she’s a very warm person. She knew how to make people feel at ease.

Keys called the collaboration “instant magic.”

I have to say, myself and Emeli Sande – when we met and we really began to write together, it was instant magic and that doesn’t happen all the time.

annotatable.link_title: Not Even the King by Alicia Keys
annotatable.title: Not Even the King

body.plain:
“Not Even the King” is track number nine off Alicia Keys’s fifth studio album Girl On Fire. This piano ballad serves as the sixth overall single from the album.

The song tells of a transcendent love that is so valuable a king could not even afford it, hence the title.

Keys wrote the song with Emeli Sandé, which was not the first time they had collaborated together. (Checkout “Hope”, “101”, and “Brand New Me”). They both had only positive things to say about each other.

Sandé explained:

 Writing with Alicia Keys was really great. I was nervous, but she’s a very warm person. She knew how to make people feel at ease.

Keys called the collaboration “instant magic.”

I have to say, myself and Emeli Sande – when we met and we really began to write together, it was instant magic and that doesn’t happen all the time.

songs.title_with_featured: Put It in a Love Song (Ft. Beyoncé)

description.plain:
“Put It In a Love Song” is the 10th track on Element of Freedom, Keys’s fourth studio album. It was slated to be the fourth official single from the project but was replaced by “Un-Thinkable (I’m Ready).” Due to the delayed release it never charted on the US Hot 100 though critics thought it was a sure fire hit.

The song features guest vocals from Beyoncé as the two sing about men needing to express their love.

description.plain:
“If I Was Your Woman/Walk On By” by Alicia Keys is a cover of “If I Were Your Woman” by Gladys Knight & the Pips that samples the same loop of Isaac Hayes' version of “Walk On By” that was sampled on The Notorious B.I.G.’s “Warning”. It appears on her second album, The Diary of Alicia Keys.

Alicia’s original demo of the cover was released in 2011 on the 10th anniversay of her debut album Songs in A Minor.

songs.full_title: Troubles by Alicia Keys
songs.title: Troubles

description.plain:
“Troubles” is track #5 on Alicia Keys’s first album, Songs in A Minor. It’s been considered “one of the more accomplished tracks on the project”.

Her troubles allude to her worries about her “hustling” boyfriend.

FUN FACT: “Troubles” was the song that triggered how she wanted to structure her feelings into an album.
duringt an interview with Rolling Stones, she added:

That’s when the album started comin' together. Finally, I knew how to structure my feelings into something that made sense, something that can translate to people. That was a changing point. My confidence was up, way up.

description.plain: “I Need You” is the tenth track from the American singer and Songwriter Alicia Keys for her third studio album, As I Am. Written and Produced by Keys Mark Baston, Harold Lilly, and Paul L Green. “Cocoa Butter' is an interlude to the next song “Girl Can’t Be Herself” and it is a snippet of men’s  conversations about stretch marks. The conclusion of this conversation is that stretch marks are just another insecurity that all humans deal with.
The interlude is an interesting look at both male and female feel insecure about their bodies.

songs.full_title: Piano & I by Alicia Keys
songs.title: Piano & I

description.plain:
“Piano & I” is the opening track on Alicia Keys' inaugural album, Songs in A Minor.

It begins with her own rendition of Ludwig van Beethoven’s “Piano Sonata No. 14” (better known as “Moonlight Sonata”) in C-sharp minor. Alicia Keys became serious with her music on the piano at the young age of 7, as she used to study Beethoven’s pieces.

This explains a dual allusion to her album’s title: the usage of a “minor” scale, and the songs that gave her a fundamental musical background as a “minor”.



The piano instrumental is later combined with another beat, giving off a hip-hop soul vibe that listeners can notice throughout the rest of the album.

The track was “leaked” to urban radio earlier in the year to introduce audiences to Alicia Keys.

songs.full_title: Mr. Man by Alicia Keys (Ft. Jimmy Cozier)
songs.title: Mr. Man

description.plain: Mr. Man contains elements Latin American music and was described as a “sexy and soulful duet”, in which Jimmy Cozier “adds his spice”. On ‘Mr Man’ she’s even doing the Latino thing. Like the analogous ‘Who Is Jill Scott?’, it’s a record of glorious parts that are just too weighty, too emotionally complex and rich to hang together well as a whole. But then, as its title suggests, it’s a collection, a compilation of moments from the five years of Alicia’s life it’s taken to complete. Taken as a kind of ‘greatest hits’ so far, it’s almost faultless.

Written and Produced Keys and Piano Vocalist Linda Perry, it was released on November 9, 2007 by J Records, it peaked the date on December 1, 2007, peaking at No. 1 for 63 weeks on the R&B chart.

description.plain: “Rock Wit U” was part of the soundtrack for the movie Shaft in 2000.  In the song, she shows her deep devotion to a man that she loves, and talks about how she will never leave him no matter what. Even if they go through extremely hard times, like she describes in verse 3, she keeps on reassuring him of her loyalty.

songs.full_title: Let It Be by Alicia Keys (Ft. John Legend)
songs.title: Let It Be

description.plain:
Alicia Keys and John Legend paid tribute to the Beatles and commemorate the 50th anniversary of the Fab Four at “The Night That Changed America: A Grammy Salute to The Beatles”.

It aired on CBS on February 9, 2014 and was reshown on February 12, 2014. The tribute, presented by the Recording Academy, AEG Ehrlich Ventures and the CBS television network, commemorated the legacy of the band and marked the 50th anniversary of their first performance on The Ed Sullivan Show. Kenneth Ehrlich served as executive producer, with Rac Clark as co-executive producer. The production was written by David Wild and Ehrlich and directed by Gregg Gelfand.

songs.full_title: When You Were Gone by Alicia Keys
songs.title: When You Were Gone

description.plain:
Excerpt from her site AliciaKeys.com, specifically, a section devoted solely to celebrating the 10-year anniversary of her album, “As I am”, named The Vault:

Finally, I have one more thing I really think you’ll LOVE!!!!! 😉 This is one of the VERY first songs I came back from Egypt and wrote. Maybe it was the second song, the first one had a whole Egyptian vibe, I’ll play that for you one day too. 😉 But this one really started to create the sound that As I Am has. We were experimenting with a lot of keyboards and sounds and styles of recording, and we were all about breaking boundaries and writing things in new ways. So please enjoy one of my favorite unreleased songs, “When You Were Gone.” <3

songs.full_title: Powerful by Alicia Keys (Ft. Jussie Smollett)
songs.title: Powerful

description.plain:
Performed by Jussie Smollett and Alicia Keys.

“Powerful” is a single from: The Empire Original Soundtrack: Season 2, Volume 1

This song symbolizes color and race.
Where Alicia talks about things going on and how both Malcolm X & Martin Luther King Jr. both made an impact, and that impact was “beautifully made.” Powerful is what we are—and as said in the lyrics “We matter, all.”
Enough shooting as she sees a brighter future where no one is at hate, but peace.
As long as we stand up, and stand together.

songs.full_title: Sweet F'in Love by Alicia Keys
songs.title: Sweet F’in Love

description.plain:
The song’s instrumentals were initially released by Kaytranada on his EP Kaytra Todo (2013) as Hot Jazzybelle.
Kaytranada has mentioned that the inspiration for the track was about a past relationship. “At one point during the song, the beat stops and you hear strings and hand claps, that describes how I’m feeling [after the breakup].”
